The greater part of the Cappadocians were, from the despotic nature of their government, actual slaves ; and the nation would seem to have been so completely wedded to servitude, that when the Romans offered them their liberty, they refused, and chose Ariobarzanes for their king. On the other hand, money was so scarce that they paid their tribute in mules and homes.— 40. Ne fueris hic tu. “ Ee not thou like him ;” i. e. do not want money as he does, but get plenty of it ! The final syllable of fueris is lengthened by the arsis—Chlumydes. The chlamys was a military eloak, generally of a purple colom-Lucullus. The famous Roman commander against Mithridates and Tigranes. The story here told is no doubt a little exaggerated, yet it is well known that Lucullus lived with a magnificence almost surpassing belief.
